{
    "analysis": "The Executor computed per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) total counts and global P95 thresholds using the full metric series, then filtered points inside the incident window. The summary output shows 15 distinct cmdb_id values (services and DBs) and 8 distinct KPI names (cpu, latency-50, latency-90, mem, socket, workload, diskio, error). The top rows are dominated by 'mem' KPIs across many components (catalogue-db, orders, shipping, queue-master, carts, etc.) with total_count=25 and incident_count=25; incident timestamps in the filtered data span from 2024-01-20T10:24:00Z to 2024-01-20T10:48:00Z (so metric sampling is available inside the incident window but starts at 10:24). This confirms we have full-series thresholds and incident-window samples available. Next, we must perform anomaly detection relative to the computed global thresholds to identify which component-KPIs actually exceed their thresholds during the window. Specifically we need anomaly counts, earliest anomaly timestamp, max severity within the window and relative breach (percent over threshold) for each component-KPI to narrow candidate root causes. None of that anomaly-level aggregation has been computed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) already computed global_p95 from the full series (do NOT recalc using only incident data). Now filter metric points to the incident window 2024-01-20 10:21:19 UTC to 2024-01-20 10:51:19 UTC. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute: 1) anomaly_count = number of incident-window points with value > global_p95; 2) anomaly_first_ts = earliest timestamp in the window where value > global_p95 (UTC datetime) or null if none; 3) anomaly_max_value = maximum metric value within the incident window; 4) percent_over = (anomaly_max_value - global_p95)/global_p95 (if global_p95==0, set percent_over to null). Also compute total_anomalous_pairs = count of (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs with anomaly_count>0. Return a table of up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc then percent_over desc, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, anomaly_count, anomaly_first_ts, anomaly_max_value, percent_over. Also return total_anomalous_pairs as a single scalar."
}

{
    "analysis": "The anomaly aggregation step found many (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pairs breaching their global P95 inside the incident window. There are 62 anomalous pairs in total. The top candidates by severity include orders/diskio (anomaly_max_value ~1.595e5, ~122.9% above global_p95), session-db/diskio, queue-master/cpu, shipping/cpu, and several latency/socket anomalies. This narrows the search to I/O (diskio), CPU and some networking/socket KPIs. Before declaring a root cause we must convert these individual anomaly points into faults (consecutive anomaly runs), remove isolated spikes and low-severity breaches (<=50% relative over-threshold), and then use traces/logs to choose among multiple faulty services. The next step is therefore to identify consecutive anomaly runs (fault candidates) for every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) that had anomaly_count>0 during the incident window, reporting run start/end, length, max severity, and percent over global_p95 so we can filter true faults from noise.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For every (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair that had anomaly_count>0 (use the previously calculated global_p95 for each pair; do NOT recompute thresholds using only incident-window data), examine metric points within the incident window 2024-01-20 10:21:19 UTC to 2024-01-20 10:51:19 UTC. Identify consecutive runs where value > global_p95 (consecutive means adjacent timestamps in the sampled series without gaps where the condition is false). For each run produce one row with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, run_start_ts (UTC), run_end_ts (UTC), run_length_minutes (number of points in the run), run_max_value, run_percent_over = (run_max_value - global_p95)/global_p95 (null if global_p95==0). Also include a boolean field run_significant = True if run_percent_over > 0.5 else False. Return up to top 20 runs sorted by run_length_minutes desc then run_percent_over desc. Also return a scalar count of distinct cmdb_id that have at least one run_significant==True within the incident window."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous steps completed metric analysis and fault identification. We calculated global P95 thresholds per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full metric series, filtered metric points to the incident window, detected anomalies, and then grouped anomalies into consecutive runs (fault candidates). The most prominent faults are: 1) orders / diskio — a 2-minute run starting 2024-01-20T10:24:00Z with run_percent_over ≈ 122.9% (significant); 2) session-db / diskio — a 1-minute run at 2024-01-20T10:48:00Z with run_percent_over ≈ 81.6% (significant). Several CPU, latency and socket anomalies of lower severity were also found but did not exceed the >50% significance threshold. According to the diagnostic workflow, the next step is trace analysis to determine service call relationships and identify which of the candidate services (the allowed root-cause set: carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) is the most downstream faulty service in traces during the incident window. Traces will help pick the root-cause service if multiple service-level faults exist.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv. Restrict analysis to the incident window 2024-01-20 10:21:19 UTC — 2024-01-20 10:51:19 UTC and to cmdb_id in the candidate service set [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"]. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute: 1) total_count (full-series point count) and global_p95 (95th percentile over the full available series), then 2) incident_count (number of points inside the incident window), 3) anomaly_count = number of incident-window points with value > global_p95, 4) anomaly_first_ts (earliest incident timestamp where value > global_p95), 5) anomaly_max_value (max value inside window), 6) percent_over = (anomaly_max_value - global_p95)/global_p95 (null if global_p95==0). Return a table limited to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc then percent_over desc with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, total_count, global_p95, incident_count, anomaly_count, anomaly_first_ts, anomaly_max_value, percent_over. Also return the list of distinct trace_name values present for these candidate services."
}

{
    "analysis": "We attempted trace analysis for the candidate services [carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user] inside the incident window and found no trace rows for those services — so traces cannot help disambiguate among service candidates. Metric analysis and fault identification already highlighted two strong metric faults: orders/diskio (2-minute run at 2024-01-20T10:24:00Z, ~122.9% over global P95) and session-db/diskio (1-minute run at 2024-01-20T10:48:00Z, ~81.6% over global P95). Multiple lower-severity CPU/latency/socket anomalies exist but are below the significance threshold (>50% over). Since traces are not available for the candidate services, the next step is log analysis to determine which service/component and resource is the root cause and whether logs indicate disk I/O, socket errors, or other reasons. We should examine both normalized log.csv metrics and raw error_logs.csv messages for the candidate services within the incident window to find corroborating evidence for the orders disk IO spike or other causes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load log.csv and error_logs.csv. First, in log.csv compute per (cmdb_id, log_name) over the full available series: total_count and global_p95 (95th percentile of 'value') — do NOT compute thresholds using only incident data. Then filter log.csv to the incident window 2024-01-20 10:21:19 UTC — 2024-01-20 10:51:19 UTC and restrict to cmdb_id in [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"]. For each (cmdb_id, log_name) produce: total_count, global_p95, incident_count, anomaly_count (incident-window points with value > global_p95), anomaly_first_ts (earliest incident ts where value > global_p95, or null), anomaly_max_value, percent_over = (anomaly_max_value - global_p95)/global_p95 (null if global_p95==0). Return up to top 20 rows sorted by anomaly_count desc then percent_over desc with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, total_count, global_p95, incident_count, anomaly_count, anomaly_first_ts, anomaly_max_value, percent_over.\n\nSecond, query error_logs.csv for any rows with cmdb_id in [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"] and timestamp inside the incident window; return up to top 50 rows with columns: timestamp (as UTC datetime), cmdb_id, message. If no rows are found, explicitly return an empty result for that query."
}

